128. Nescio quis Theseus. ‘ Oenone, ut mulier pere- grina, fingit se non satis nosse Theseum' R. The story, as

narrated by Apollodorus, is simply this. The fame of Helen's beauty being bruited abroad over Greece, Theseus, assisted by Pirithous, bore her away by force and transported her to Athens. He then descended to the infernal regions for the purpose ot' aiding his friend to carry off Proserpine. Meanwhile Castor and Pollux made war against Athens, captured the city, recovered their sister, and, in retaliation‚ led prisoner to Sparta, Aethra, the mother of Theseus.
